    "summary": "Vasco da Gama's voyage to India (1497–1499 AD) was the first direct sea route connection between Western Europe and Asia, rounding the Cape of Good Hope (previously rounded by [[event:3056|Bartholomew Dias]] in 1488) and reaching Calicut on India's Malabar Coast in May 1498 — achieving the great objective of Portuguese exploration that had been pursued systematically for nearly a century under [[event:3055|Henry the Navigator's]] program. The voyage demonstrated that all-water trade routes between Europe and Asia were viable, bypassing the Ottoman-controlled overland routes and the Arab and Venetian middlemen who dominated the existing spice trade.\n\nDa Gama's arrival in India transformed the global spice trade with startling speed. Within a decade, Portuguese warships had established control over key Indian Ocean chokepoints — Hormuz, Goa, Malacca — disrupting the Arab commercial networks that had linked the Indian Ocean to the Mediterranean for centuries and creating the Portuguese Estado da India, the first European oceanic empire in Asia. The pepper and spices that had been the most valuable traded commodities in the medieval world were now available to Europe at dramatically lower cost, ruining the fortunes of Venice and the Levantine trade cities that had grown wealthy as intermediaries. Da Gama's voyage was made possible by the cumulative Portuguese navigational expertise developed over sixty years of African exploration, the development of the caravel ship suited to open-ocean sailing, and the introduction of artillery-equipped warships that gave the Portuguese decisive military superiority over the local Arab and Indian naval forces they encountered.",
